  "text": "The LLVM SelectionDAG type expansion logic involves several key components:\n\n1. **SelectionDAGLegalize class (llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeDAG.cpp)**: This is the main class that orchestrates the legalization of SelectionDAG nodes. The ExpandNode function (line 3218) handles type expansion operations. The LegalizeDAG.cpp file contains the implementation of the SelectionDAGLegalize class which is responsible for transforming the DAG to use only legal types.\n\n2. **EVT (Extended Value Type) class (llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/ValueTypes.h)**: Defines the extended value type representation. The isSimple() method (line 136-138) checks if a type is a simple MVT or an extended type. This is critical for determining whether a type can be expanded or needs special handling.\n\n3. **Type legalization flow in TargetLoweringBase (llvm/lib/CodeGen/TargetLoweringBase.cpp)**: The getTypeConversion function (line 1329) is the core of type legalization strategy. It determines whether a type should be promoted, expanded, split, widened, or scalarized based on target capabilities. When a type cannot be expanded (e.g., if it's not simple and lacks proper expansion hooks), the function will either return a legalization action or trigger an assertion.\n\n4. **TargetLowering::getTypeToExpandTo (llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/TargetLowering.h)**: This function at line 1185 determines the type that a non-legal type will be expanded to. It contains an assertion at line 1195: 'llvm_unreachable(\"Type is not legal nor is it to be expanded!\")' which fires when a type cannot be properly expanded.\n\nThe error \"Cannot expand this type; LLVM lacks the right hooks\" typically occurs when the type legalization process reaches a type that cannot be handled by the target's configured legal types and expansion hooks. This happens when:\n- A type is not simple (not an MVT) and is extended\n- The target has not defined proper expansion hooks for complex types\n- The type cannot be transformed into legal types through promotion, expansion, splitting, or other legalization strategies\n\nThe chain of expansion involves ExpandNode checking with target lowering hooks (TLI functions like expandABS, expandCTPOP, etc.), which delegate to TargetLowering's expansion methods that rely on the type conversion framework defined in TargetLoweringBase."
}

